Fig. 4
A shows the normalized RT PL and PLE spectra of HDPE. Upon UV (325 nm) excitation, the polymeric host, consisting of chains of a single bonded monomer unit [CH2
], exhibited a well-structured emission band in the UV/blue spectral range. With a reported RT bandgap energy between 5.9 to 8 eV [52–54], the insulating HDPE is expected to present only absorption in the deep UV, in the absence of defects. Nevertheless, this crystalline polymer is known to present a myriad of intrinsic and extrinsic defects, leading to electronic energy levels inside the material gap, which can trap carriers or promote internal radiative transitions, strongly influencing its electrical and optical properties [53–57].
